We recommended that Management require:
The GSO to conduct the physical count of inventories semestrally and submit the report to the Audit Team within the prescribed period. The RPCI shall be reconciled with the records maintained by the Accounting;
The Municipal Accountant and GSO to maintain the supplies ledger card and stock cards, respectively, and observe proper inventory management and internal control procedures in accordance with the NGAS Manual for LGUs;
The Municipal Accountant to prepare adjusting entries to take up the distribution of Medical, Dental and Laboratory Supplies and Property and Equipment for Distribution to the barangay beneficiaries and ensure to attach the supporting documents, in accordance with PPSASs 12 Inventories.

We recommended that Management make the necessary confirmation with concerned agencies whose names still appear in the listing of outstanding funds which remain in the books of the Municipality to ascertain the action to be taken onions, viz;
Return to the concerned source agencies the unutilized balance of the fund transfer wherein the agreement requires the return thereof;
Revert to Government Equity the balances of fund transfers in the nature of financial assistance and subsidy wherein the agreement does not mention of the disposition of the unused balance and that future utilization thereof will be subject to the usual accounting, auditing and budgeting laws, rules and regulations;
Retain special purpose fund; and
Clean the books of accounts, particularly the account Due to NGAs, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005 in order to present fairly the Liability accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management require:
The Accounting Office to prepare adjusting entries to correct the recording of unpaid water fees as of December 31, 2020 and henceforth, apply the accrual basis in recording revenues in accordance with the PPSASs;
The Treasury Office to provide the Accounting Office with the details of monthly water system fees as basis for the recording of receivables and revenue, and copy of the Municipal Revenue Ordinance for the collection of water system fees;
The Accounting and Treasury Office to reconcile the noted difference of ₱96,641.00.

We recommend that Management require the:

Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to reconcile their records of the PPE accounts and make the necessary adjustments thereto; 

Further, for both officials to maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, in accordance with the forms prescribed in Annexes 9 and 37 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II. Henceforth, conduct periodic reconciliation of their respective records, at least on a quarterly basis, to ensure accuracy of the PPE accounts;

Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory of the Municipality’s properties. Thereafter, prepare the RPCPPE in the prescribed form and submit the same to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year; and

General Services Officer to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) of the identified unserviceable properties as initial step in the disposal thereof.  Thereafter, proceed with the disposal of the same in accordance with existing regulations in order that only serviceable properties remain in the books as PPE.

We recommended that Management:

Continue its effort in titling the remaining 14 lots in the name of the Municipality;

Appropriate funds in the LGU’s annual budget to cover related costs in the registration of these 14 real properties;

Require the Inventory Team to prepare a complete inventory report of PPEs, including the real properties, and reconcile the report with the GSO records. Thereafter, furnish the Audit Team a copy of the report;

Instruct the General Services Officer to indicate in the RPCPPE complete information relative to these lots to facilitate the reconciliation of the report with the accounting records.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendations that the Local Chief Executive require:

The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to provide the LSB the certified statement containing the following reports, for the latter to properly compute the amount available for appropriation, namely: (a) actual SEF Income for the immediately preceding fiscal year; (b) actual SEF income for the first two quarters of the current year; (c) the estimated SEF income for the last two quarters of the current year; and (d) the annual estimates for the ensuing year;

The Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records to arrive at a reliable and accurate SAAOB;

The LSB the early submission of the complete School Improvement Plans by the school heads, indicating therein the priority needs of the schools based on DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017, together with budget matrix showing its sources, in order that the same may be considered in the preparation of the SEF Budget;

The LSB formulate/prepare the required three-year strategic program and SIPs which are necessary input in the preparation of the SEF Annual Budget and also furnish the Audit Team of the same for reference and review purposes; and

The LSB to strictly adhere to the prescribed formula in the computation of the available appropriation for SEF.

We recommended that Management require:

The Municipal Assessor’s Office to provide the MTO with the latest total assessment valuation as well as the taxes to be imposed;

The concerned offices to prepare periodic reports to monitor the status of revenue generation and to serve as guide on the appropriate measures to be adopted in case of shortfall in the projected revenue targets; 

The MTO and the MAO to reconcile the monthly and quarterly reports and recording of accounts in order to arrive at timely and accurate reports; and

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that Management:

Request the SB to pass an ordinance prescribing the guidelines, rules and regulations, standard fees/rates and others for market and the water system operations. Such ordinance shall be included in the updated Local Revenue Tax Code of the Municipality; 


Ensure that stallholders and consumers have valid contracts/agreements before the allowing them to avail of the market stalls and water services to protect the interest of the Municipality;

Formulate effective and practical strategies to enhance collection of all unpaid accounts from market and the water system operations and impose penalties/surcharges against defaulting lessees/consumers; and

Direct the offices of the Treasurer, Market and MAWASA to properly coordinate their activities with regard to market and water system operations and to reconcile existing records.

We recommended that the LCE;

Initiate and apply measures in upgrading the data system in the updating of the Municipal Treasurer’s Office records for immediate identifying delinquent taxpayer and formulate effective measures in the collections of taxes; and


Direct the Treasurer and the Offices of the Market and Water System Administrator to submit immediately to the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO) a report or list of the total uncollected fees of ₱116,820 and ₱0.77 million, on the market stall rental and water supply services, respectively and henceforth all accounts for recording purposes and to maintain regularly a complete and updated individual subsidiary ledgers of all market stallholders/water supply and distribution clients;

We also recommended that Management direct the Municipal Assessor to furnish the Treasurer’s Office with a computerized assessment roll to facilitate fast and efficient generation of the Certified List;

We recommend that Management require the:
Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to reconcile their records  of the PPE accounts and make the necessary adjustments thereto;
Further, for both officials to maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, in accordance with the forms prescribed in Annexes 9 and 37 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II. Henceforth, conduct periodic reconciliation of their respective records, at least on a quarterly basis, to ensure accuracy of the PPE accounts;
Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory of the Municipality’s properties. Thereafter, prepare the RPCPPE in the prescribed form and submit the same to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year; and
General Services Officer to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) of the identified unserviceable properties as initial step in the disposal thereof.  Thereafter, proceed with the disposal of the same in accordance with existing regulations in order that only serviceable properties remain in the books as PPE.

We recommended that Management:
Continue its effort in titling the remaining 14 lots in the name of the Municipality;
Appropriate funds in the LGU’s annual budget to cover related costs in the registration of these 14 real properties;
Require the Inventory Team to prepare a complete inventory report of PPEs, including the real properties, and reconcile the report with the GSO records. Thereafter, furnish the Audit Team a copy of the report;
Instruct the General Services Officer to indicate in the RPCPPE complete information relative to these lots to facilitate the reconciliation of the report with the accounting records.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendations that the Local Chief Executive require:
The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to provide the LSB the certified statement containing the following reports, for the latter to properly compute the amount available for appropriation, namely: (a) actual SEF Income for the immediately preceding fiscal year; (b) actual SEF income for the first two quarters of the current year; (c) the estimated SEF income for the last two quarters of the current year; and (d) the annual estimates for the ensuing year;
The Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records to arrive at a reliable and accurate SAAOB;
The LSB the early submission of the complete School Improvement Plans by the school heads, indicating therein the priority needs of the schools based on DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017, together with budget matrix showing its sources, in order that the same may be considered in the preparation of the SEF Budget;
The LSB formulate/prepare the required three-year strategic program and SIPs which are necessary input in the preparation of the SEF Annual Budget and also furnish the Audit Team of the same for reference and review purposes; and
The LSB to strictly adhere to the prescribed formula in the computation of the available appropriation for SEF.

For the deficiencies noted, we recommended that:

The Municipal Treasurer continue coordinating with the Municipal Accountant for the complete and immediate reconciliation of the individual balances of the cash accounts in the GL and cashbooks, particularly the prior years’ balances and make the necessary adjustments thereon. Likewise, for the Municipal Accountant to always provide the MTO updated BRS and all the necessary documents needed for reconciliation. Henceforth, in compliance with Section 189 of the GAAM, the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant shall reconcile their records, at least quarterly, to avoid incurrence of accumulated unreconciled balances:

The Municipal Treasurer to maintain a cashbook for Payroll Fund account to serve as records of its transactions and ensure complete and systematic monitoring of the Cash-in Bank account;

The Municipal Accountant to record all reconciling items in the books to fairly present the Cash accounts in the financial statements;

We also recommended that Management take appropriate remedial measures, such as augmenting the personnel at the MTO to assist the Municipal Treasurer in the reconciliation of the cashbook balance with the cash on hand daily and with the Accounting records at least quarterly.

We recommended that Management require:

The concerned offices to prepare a systematic, comprehensive and realistic revenue forecasting system taking into account prior years and the tax information system of the local government;

The Municipal Accountant to provide the concerned officials involved in preparation of the Annual Budget with a copy of the Chart of Account under PPSAS;

The Municipal Treasurer to follow forecasting guidelines set by the BLGF;

The Municipal Assessor’s Office to provide the MTO with the latest total assessment valuation as well as the taxes to be imposed;

The concerned offices to prepare periodic reports to monitor the status of revenue generation and to serve as guide on the appropriate measures to be adopted in case of shortfall in the projected revenue targets; 

The MTO and the MAO to reconcile the monthly and quarterly reports and recording of accounts in order to arrive at timely and accurate reports; and

The MAO review and prepare necessary adjusting journal entries to correct recording of the account Miscellaneous Income

